│ stop({"edit_points": [[2111, 2115, "llvm/lib/Transforms/Coroutines/CoroSplit.cpp"]],   │
│ "thoughts": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe crash occurs with an assertion in        │
│ updateCGAndAnalysisManagerForPass complaining that the current SCC was invalidated:    │
│ `!UR.InvalidatedSCCs.count(C)`. This is a CGSCC invariant violation—function-level     │
│ updates are not allowed to invalidate the SCC currently being processed. The           │
│ reproducer involves mutually recursive coroutines, and the first logged transformation │
│ is switching an internal ref edge to a call edge from 'foo' to 'bar', which can change │
│ SCC membership or structure.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe debug log shows:\n-       │
│ \"Running an SCC pass across the RefSCC: [(foo), (bar)]\"\n- \"CoroSplit: Processing   │
│ coroutine 'foo\"\n- \"Switch an internal ref edge to a call edge from 'foo' to         │
│ 'bar'\"\nImmediately after, we hit the assertion in                                    │
│ updateCGAndAnalysisManagerForPass.\nIn CoroSplit's updateCallGraphAfterCoroutineSplit, │
│ we first notify the CG about clones using                                              │
│ CG.addSplitFunction/addSplitRefRecursiveFunctions and then call                        │
│ updateCGAndAnalysisManagerForCGSCCPass (safe for SCC changes). After that, we run      │
│ postSplitCleanup and then call updateCGAndAnalysisManagerForFunctionPass. The latter   │
│ is intended for function-level updates that do not invalidate the current SCC.         │
│ However, the cleanup can precipitate an edge change (ref->call), as logged, within the │
│ same SCC, which may invalidate it.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nThe root cause is that  │
│ updateCallGraphAfterCoroutineSplit calls updateCGAndAnalysisManagerForFunctionPass     │
│ after postSplitCleanup, even in situations where this cleanup can trigger changes in   │
