  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe crash occurs with an assertion in
updateCGAndAnalysisManagerForPass complaining that the current SCC was invalidated:
`!UR.InvalidatedSCCs.count(C)`. This is a CGSCC invariant violation\u2014function-level
updates are not allowed to invalidate the SCC currently being processed. The reproducer
involves mutually recursive coroutines, and the first logged transformation is switching
an internal ref edge to a call edge from 'foo' to 'bar', which can change SCC membership
or structure.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe debug log shows:\n- \"Running an SCC pass
across the RefSCC: [(foo), (bar)]\"\n- \"CoroSplit: Processing coroutine 'foo\"\n-
\"Switch an internal ref edge to a call edge from 'foo' to 'bar'\"\nImmediately after, we
hit the assertion in updateCGAndAnalysisManagerForPass.\nIn CoroSplit's
updateCallGraphAfterCoroutineSplit, we first notify the CG about clones using
CG.addSplitFunction/addSplitRefRecursiveFunctions and then call
updateCGAndAnalysisManagerForCGSCCPass (safe for SCC changes). After that, we run
postSplitCleanup and then call updateCGAndAnalysisManagerForFunctionPass. The latter is
intended for function-level updates that do not invalidate the current SCC. However, the
cleanup can precipitate an edge change (ref->call), as logged, within the same SCC, which
may invalidate it.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nThe root cause is that
updateCallGraphAfterCoroutineSplit calls updateCGAndAnalysisManagerForFunctionPass after
postSplitCleanup, even in situations where this cleanup can trigger changes in the call
graph that invalidate the SCC (e.g., converting a ref edge to a call edge between nodes
within the SCC). In such cases, updateCGAndAnalysisManagerForFunctionPass asserts because
it requires that the current SCC remains valid. For mutually recursive coroutines, this
ref->call edge change is precisely what occurs, leading to SCC invalidation in a
function-pass update context.\n\nThe CGSCC infrastructure provides two update helpers:\n-
updateCGAndAnalysisManagerForCGSCCPass: safe when the SCC may be invalidated or structural
changes occur.\n- updateCGAndAnalysisManagerForFunctionPass: expects no SCC
invalidation.\n\nWe already use the CGSCC variant for handling clones. We must also use
the CGSCC variant after cleanup if edges can change in ways that could invalidate the
SCC.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\nEdit file llvm/lib/Transforms/Coroutines/CoroSplit.cpp
at lines 2111-2115.\nCurrent code:\n  // Do some cleanup and let the CGSCC infra see if
we've cleaned up any edges\n  // to the split functions.\n
postSplitCleanup(N.getFunction());\n  updateCGAndAnalysisManagerForFunctionPass(CG, C, N,
AM, UR, FAM);\n\nChange to:\n  // Do some cleanup and let the CGSCC infra see if we've
cleaned up any edges\n  // to the split functions. This may refine internal edges (e.g.,
switch a\n  // ref edge to a call edge) and potentially invalidate the current SCC.\n  //
Use the CGSCC update helper to safely handle SCC changes.\n
postSplitCleanup(N.getFunction());\n  updateCGAndAnalysisManagerForCGSCCPass(CG, C, N, AM,
UR, FAM);\n\nRationale:\n- After postSplitCleanup, edges can change (as evidenced by the
debug message), and using the function-pass updater triggers the assertion. Switching to
the CGSCC updater allows SCC invalidation and properly updates the analysis manager and
worklists.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nThe fix ensures that any call graph changes arising from
postSplitCleanup are handled with the CGSCC-aware update helper, avoiding the
invalidation-while-in-function-pass assertion. This preserves the CGSCC invariants and
prevents the crash when mutually recursive coroutines cause the edge to switch from ref to
call during coro-split.",
